CXLVII. DE ENDYMIONIS PORTERI CUBICULARII REGII CONIUGE, CAL. IAN. EX ANGLICO.

Armeniam venare feram, pretiosaque terga Endymioneae munera mitte Deae. His Dea donetur, quamvis sit mollior ipsa Qualibet Armenia candidiorque fera. Scande iuga, et si quae stella est in rupibus illis, Cui radios adamas contrahit igne brevi, Hanc dabis inventam Divae, quae vincit ocellis, Alta Iovis quidquid regia lucis habet. Eois te merge vadis, quaeratur in illis Unio, quem caeli rore tumere vides. 10 Unio quaeratur praestringens lumina regum, Et, quascunque tegunt aequora, vincat opes. Hunc quoque da Divae, quamvis pretiosior illi Lacrima sit gemmis, quas dare concha potest. Regia quarn vates hic do mandata? ministri Quam lentas adhibent ad mea iussa manus! CXLVIII. ON A LADY VOYAGING, FROM THE ENGLISH.

Subject or original has not been traced.

ARGUMENT.

Farewell‚ Goddess: let the sea cease to bring back the dew into mine eyes or the breeze to echo my sighings3 but may Thetis emulating thy bland look gaze placidly upon thee, and gently let the south wind breathe in thine ear. Let no bold wave heave himself high in Ocean and presume to come near to taste thy lip. Ah, my fear is that Love may affect both billow and breeze, and both rising high may trouble the main.
